TY  - JOUR
T1  - Computational Experience with an M-Salesman Traveling Salesman Algorithm
AU  - Svestka, Joseph A.
AU  - Huckfeldt, Vaughn E.
Y1  - 1973/03/01
PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.19.7.790
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.19.7.790
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 790
EP  - 799
VL  - 19
IS  - 7
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - A formulation of the traveling salesman problem with more than one salesman is offered. The particular formulation has computational advantages over other formulations. Experience is obtained with an exact branch and bound algorithm employing both upper and lower bounds (mean run time for 55 city problems is one minute). Due to the special formulation, certain subtours may satisfy the constraints, thus reducing the search. A very good initial tour and upper bound are employed. The determination of these as well as the pathology of the formulation and the algorithm are discussed. No increase in computation time over the one-salesman case is experienced.
AB  - A formulation of the traveling salesman problem with more than one salesman is offered. The particular formulation has computational advantages over other formulations. Experience is obtained with an exact branch and bound algorithm employing both upper and lower bounds (mean run time for 55 city problems is one minute). Due to the special formulation, certain subtours may satisfy the constraints, thus reducing the search. A very good initial tour and upper bound are employed. The determination of these as well as the pathology of the formulation and the algorithm are discussed. No increase in computation time over the one-salesman case is experienced.
